    <item>V wins 33 first place votes; S, 36; D, 31; and T, 0. So candidate S, “Put into savings,” has a plurality and wins. Since the Condorcet candidate D didn’t win, the Condorcet criterion is violated.</item>
    <item>Use the steps outlined in <link target-id="sect-00005" document="m00025">Ranked-Choice Voting</link> for determining the winner of an election by ranked-choice voting, the application of the Hare method in which instant runoffs are used.
    <para id="para-00034"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 1:</emphasis> The number of votes needed to achieve a majority is 51.</para>
    <para id="para-00035"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 2:</emphasis> As illustrated in part 1, no candidate has a majority of first-place votes; so the candidate with the fewest votes, T, must be eliminated.</para>
